Have you ever heard of molotes? They are a common street food found in Oaxaca, Puebla, and the Yucatan.

When I first heard the word “molotes” I thought of hair buns, because that’s what we call them. I’ve seen cigar and torpedo-shaped molotes and balls of dough similar to hush puppies (or hair buns 😂), but shaping them like empanadas is the easiest to achieve at home.

These molotes are filled with chicken tinga inspired after my trip to Puebla. In Puebla they slow cook their tomatoes until they are sweeter and more of a thickened sauce and then they also add piloncillo giving the tinga a hint of sweetness which really balances out the spicy and smoky chipotles. 

Find the recipe on my blog: https://muybuenocookbook.com/molotes-oaxacan-masa-empanadas/

🇧🇷 Have you ever heard of Feijoada? The word feijoada comes from the word feijão, which is Portuguese for beans. Often considered the national dish of Brazil, feijoada (pronounced “FAY-jwa-duh”) is a deliciously rustic black bean stew that is peppered with multiple types of meat like smoked pork, beef, and at least two kinds of sausage. Feijoada is similar to a jambalaya.

I learned about this delightful Brazilian dish from my friend Sonia. She hosts a party every year where feijoada is served, and I was lucky enough for her to share her family recipe with me.

This one-pot dish is an inexpensive way to feed a crowd. Plus, the prep work only takes 15 minutes, making it easy enough for even a busy weeknight. 

The meal is just as warm, comforting, rich and vibrant as the music, people and culture of Brazil.

RECIPE: https://muybuenocookbook.com/brazilian-feijoada/

This marbled and twirly-topped bread is a cross between a Christmas star and a rosca de reyes, or “king’s cake,” a wreath-shaped cake that is traditionally baked for Día de los Reyes in Mexico. The bread is decorated with candied fruits to symbolize the “jewels” on a crown and has a small plastic or ceramic figure tucked inside to represent the baby Jesus. Known as Epiphany in other parts of the world, Día de los Reyes falls on January 6 and celebrates the visit the Three Wise Men made to Bethlehem to bring gifts to the baby Jesus. The custom is that whoever finds the figurine in his or her serving of the bread must host a party on Día de la Candelaria (Candlemas Day), a Christian festival day celebrated on February 2 at which tamales are traditionally served.

Needing an easy Valentine’s Day cocktail? Here ya go !! Bright, deliciously minty, and a perfect balance of sweet and tart, this Strawberry Lemonade and Tequila Smash might just be my new favorite cocktail.

🍓 3 strawberries, hulled
🍓 8 fresh mint leaves
🍓 1/2 lemon, juiced
🍓 1.5 ounces tequila (silver or reposado)
🍓 1 ounce agave nectar
🍓 Lemon slice and mint for garnish

Place the strawberries and mint into a cocktail shaker. Using a muddler (or the back of a wooden spoon), thoroughly mash the two ingredients, allowing the strawberry juices to release.

Then add in the lemon juice, tequila, and agave nectar. Seal the lid onto the cocktail shaker and shake vigorously for 30 seconds.

Place sugar on a small plate. Line the rim of a double old-fashioned glass (or similar) with a lemon wedge and then dip into the sugar to coat the rim of the glass.

Fill the glass halfway with crushed ice. Then pour the strawberry mixture over it. Top with additional ice. Garnish with a lemon slice and fresh mint. Serve immediately.

Mexican bread pudding, or capirotada, is a very special dish that I look forward to every Lenten season. My grandma and mom always made capirotada with cinnamon, piloncillo, cloves, raisins, cheese, and bread. In the first “Muy Bueno” cookbook and on this blog you’ll find our heavenly capirotada family recipe.

In my new cookbook, “Muy Bueno Fiestas” you’ll find a recipe for Tres Leches Capirotada with Bourbon Sauce — its a delicious fusion of two classic Mexican desserts, capirotada (bread pudding) and the rich three-milks mixture known as tres leches.

I skip the cheese, and I soak the bread in a tres leches mixture in addition to the traditional cinnamon-infused piloncillo syrup, plus I soak the raisins in bourbon. But the richness doesn’t end there. When the pudding emerges from the oven, I drizzle a bourbon sauce on top. Even though my mom is a traditionalist, she admitted that she is impressed and might even prefer my modern boozy capirotada, but that could have been the bourbon talking.

The Tres Leches Capirotada recipe is in “Muy Bueno Fiestas”! Grab your copy TODAY! Please know I am so grateful for your support of this cookbook. I know this cookbook will inspire you to host, entertain, but most of all get in the kitchen!

Tornado warnings in Colorado today, but I’m gonna pretend we have sunny skies and enjoy a Pineapple Tequila Spritzer 🍍

Pineapple juice with effervescence from a healthy splash of mineral water, my Pineapple Tequila Spritzer is as much a thirst-quencher as it is a happy hour hero.

Made with just 4 ingredients in less than 5 minutes, this tropically-inspired tequila pineapple cocktail will quickly reset your internal clock to Island Time.

▢ 1 ½ ounces mezcal or tequila
▢ 1 ½  ounces fresh lemon juice
▢ 1 ½  ounces pineapple juice
▢ Mineral water

Add mezcal or tequila, lemon juice, pineapple juice to a cocktail shaker filled with ice and shake for about 30 seconds.

Strain into a glass over large ice cubes and top with mineral water. Garnish with a pineapple leaf, if desired.

Lately, I’ve been thinking about my dad a lot, and it feels like he’s sending me a gentle reminder to keep his memory alive. You might know from my online stories that I often talk about my grandma and mom, who were a big part of my upbringing. But I know some of you have wondered about my dad, who passed away earlier this year.

The story of my relationship with my dad is a bit complex. My parents were married only until I was two years old. Then, seven years later, they reunited when I was 10, only to divorce again when I turned 15. So, in total, my dad was physically present in my life for about six years. Typically, we saw each other primarily during holidays or when I visited El Paso, and our conversations averaged about once a month. And of course, there was the weekly tradition of receiving a dad joke text from him.

But that doesn’t mean we weren’t close in our unique way. I really looked up to him because he knew how to enjoy life’s simple pleasures. He was all about cars, motorcycles, and boats, and he had this incredible talent for building engines from scratch. Besides, he had a knack for business, and whenever we talked, our conversations often revolved around our ventures. He truly got my determination and drive.

After my parents’ second divorce, he tied the knot again and welcomed three more children into his life. I was in my late twenties, on the verge of starting my own family, and it feels like those years simply raced past us.

Time flew by while he was here on Earth. Even though I didn’t see or talk to my dad as much as I’d have liked, he was still my dad. I just wish we had more time together. Life has a way of moving fast, leaving us with memories as our most precious treasure.

I’ll be heading to El Paso next week, and I plan to take a drive through the pecan orchards in Mesilla, New Mexico while listening to oldies but goodies, just like my dad and I used to do in his cool Corvette. It’s a way for me to feel closer to him, to relive those moments we shared, and to cherish the memories we created together.

Many people in the United States commonly mistake Cinco de Mayo for Mexican Independence Day. But while Cinco de Mayo celebrates a single victory in 1862 over the French in the ongoing Franco-Mexican War—a war that Mexico eventually lost—September 16 represents the beginning of an historic eleven-year war against Spain that ended with Mexico’s independence.

In the United States, Mexican Independence Day, which kicks off National Hispanic Heritage Month, is celebrated in much the same way as the Fourth of July—with fireworks, music, dancing, family get-togethers, and, of course, lots of delicious food and drink.

Sweet and tangy Agua de Tamarindo is the perfect Mexican beverage for the day. It’s deeply refreshing, nonalcoholic, and ideal for cleansing the palate for my Tequila Tasting Party. It also happens to make a mean cocktail! As for food, creamy Chiles en Nogada, a specialty of Puebla, and Flautas de Carne Deshebrada a la Bandera, which are topped with green salsa, Mexican crema, and tomato broth—the colors of the Mexican flag—are two delicious celebratory dishes everyone will enjoy.

Regardless of whether or not you share any Hispanic heritage, I hope you will take this opportunity to send summer off in style. After all, we can all use more fiestas! 

From my family to yours, Feliz Día de la Independencia, y Viva México!

Is it "tamale" or "tamal?"

In Mexican Spanish, the correct singular term for this beloved dish is "tamal," while the plural form is "tamales." This usage stems from the word's origin in the Nahuatl language, where "tamalli" is used as a general term for the dish, not distinguishing between singular and plural. 

The word "tamale," commonly used in English, is actually an Anglicized adaptation. As the dish traveled and gained popularity in different regions, the terminology evolved, leading to these variations in its name. Regardless of the term used, the deliciousness of this dish remains a universal language for food lovers everywhere!

Correct Mexican Spanish usage can be a topic of debate. That said, I rarely use "tamal" — because who stops at just eating one tamal, right?
